    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've also been reading about the criticisms of it. people seem to say originalism is just a way for judges to push their own political agendas under the guise of \"fixed meaning.\" how do scholars respond to that claim that it's more about politics than actual law?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics who claim originalism is merely a political disguise fundamentally misunderstand the concept of objective legal meaning. Originalists argue that adhering to the original public meaning is the *only* way to maintain judicial restraint and prevent judges from imposing their personal, subjective policy preferences onto the text. To suggest otherwise is to argue that the Constitution is a malleable political document, which is a dangerous and unprincipled view of law.",
